::end


::step id="intro" title="The closed-loop learning piece"

::explain
This project builds the first closed-loop learning piece.

Current system:

User goal
-> Mastra agent
-> real DB tools
-> AgentRun
-> TraceSpan

Now we add:

AgentRun + TraceSpan
-> LLM reads raw evidence
-> structured failure diagnosis
-> FailureCluster row

No hardcoded classification.
::end

::checkpoint id="intro-done"
You now understand the loop we are building.
::end

::end


::step id="create-failure-agent" title="Create the failure analyst agent"

::explain
Now create a separate analyst agent.

This is not the ops agent.
It has no tools.

Its job is only to read trace evidence and produce a structured diagnosis.
::end

::edit id="failure-agent-file" path="mastra/agents/failure-analyst-agent.ts" mode="create" typing="ghost"
```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";

export const failureAnalystAgent = new Agent({
  id: "failure-analyst-agent",
  name: "Failure Analyst Agent",
  instructions: `
You analyze traces from tool-using agents.

Your job is not to summarize the run.
Your job is to decide whether the trace contains a reusable failure pattern.
`,
  model: "google/gemini-2.5-flash",
});
```
::end

::checkpoint id="failure-agent-created"
The analyst agent now exists.
::end

::end


::step id="create-failure-schema" title="Create the failure extraction schema"

::explain
Now define the structured output contract.

The model cannot ramble. It has to return a validated object.

The important field is `shouldCreateCluster`, because a learning system that turns every run into a fake lesson becomes noisy.
::end

::edit id="failure-schema-file" path="lib/failure-extraction.ts" mode="create" typing="ghost"
```ts
import { z } from "zod";

export const failureExtractionSchema = z.object({
  shouldCreateCluster: z.boolean(),
  reason: z.string(),
  title: z.string(),
  failureClass: z.enum([
    "auth_failure",
    "schema_failure",
    "prompt_drift",
    "retry_loop",
    "early_success",
    "bad_tool_choice",
    "missing_information",
    "unknown",
  ]),
  trigger: z.string(),
  evidence: z.string(),
  severity: z.enum(["low", "medium", "high"]),
  suggestedFix: z.string(),
});

export type FailureExtraction = z.infer<typeof failureExtractionSchema>;

export function buildFailureExtractionPrompt(input: {
  run: unknown;
  spans: unknown[];
}) {
  return [
    "Analyze this agent run and its trace spans.",
    "",
    "Decide whether there is a reusable failure pattern worth saving.",
    "",
    "If the run succeeded cleanly, set shouldCreateCluster to false.",
    "If there is a real agent reliability issue, set shouldCreateCluster to true.",
    "",
    "Agent run:",
    JSON.stringify(input.run, null, 2),
    "",
    "Trace spans:",
    JSON.stringify(input.spans, null, 2),
  ].join("\n");
}
```
::end

::checkpoint id="failure-schema-created"
The structured failure extraction contract now exists.
::end

::end


::step id="run-test" title="Test the extraction flow"

::explain
Now use the real terminal at the bottom to run the project commands.

A clean run should usually return `created: false`.

That abstention matters.
::end

::run id="seed-db" cwd="."
npm run seed
::end

::run id="start-dev" cwd="."
npm run dev
::end

::expect id="clean-output" type="manual"
After creating a clean run and calling the extraction endpoint, you should see something like:

{
  "created": false,
  "reason": "..."
}
::end

::checkpoint id="project-complete"
You now have the first version of trace-to-failure learning.
::end

::end
